thread.title: Top 25 roundup: TCU rallies for 52-45 win over Kansas State

title: Top 25 roundup: TCU rallies for 52-45 win over Kansas State
text:
Cubs even series against Cards 
The Horned Frogs outscored the Wildcats 35-10 after the intermission. TCU quarterback Trevone Boykin connected with Doctson for a 55-yard touchdown for the game-winner with 1:10 remaining. 
Kansas State had a streak of 49 straight victories when leading at halftime snapped last week at Oklahoma State. 
No. 1 Ohio State 49, Maryland 28 
COLUMBUS, Ohio -- Ohio State used its array of quarterbacks to hold off the upset bid of Maryland as the top-ranked Buckeyes pulled away from an early third-quarter tie with 28 consecutive points. 
Cardale Jones passed for two touchdowns, backup J.T. Barrett ran for three in red-zone situations and wide receiver and former quarterback Braxton Miller caught a touchdown pass. 
Maryland quarterback Perry Hills, in his first start in four games, ran for touchdowns late in the first half and to open the third quarter to rally Maryland into a 21-21 tie. 
No. 3 Baylor 66, Kansas 7 
LAWRENCE, Kan. -- Seth Russell passed for 246 yards and three touchdowns and Shock Linwood added 135 yards rushing as Baylor stomped Kansas. 
Russell and Linwood played only in the first half. They were among several Baylor regulars who returned to the sideline for the second half without wearing pads. 
The Bears needed slightly more than two minutes to drive 75 yards for their first touchdown and went on to score on each of their first eight possessions. 
No. 4 Michigan State 31, Rutgers 24 
PISCATAWAY, N.J. -- The Spartans received a scare, but the offense did just enough to secure the victory. 
Freshman L.J. Scott scored on a 3-yard off-tackle run with 43 seconds to play, giving the Spartans their school-record 11th straight conference road win. 
Rutgers bid for a tying score ended at midfield when quarterback Chris Laviano inexplicably spiked the ball on fourth down with three seconds to play. 
No. 5 Utah 30, No. 23 Cal 24 
SALT LAKE CITY -- Utah hung on to defeat California when a pass by Jared Goff was broken up on fourth-and-5 in the final seconds. 
Devontae Booker was the star on homecoming night for the Utes with 267 all-purpose yards, including a season-high 222 rushing yards, two touchdowns and a fumble. 
Goff threw a career-high five interceptions but completed 25 of 47 passes for 340 yards and two touchdowns. In all, Utah's defense had six takeaways. 
Cal cut the deficit to 27-24 with 2:03 remaining in the third quarter after Booker's third-quarter fumble led to a 4-yard touchdown run by running back Tre Watson. 
No. 6 Clemson 43, Georgia Tech 24 
CLEMSON, S.C. -- Deshaun Watson threw for 265 yards and two touchdowns and the Tigers' defense throttled the Yellow Jacket's potent option rushing attack. 
Clemson, which has led the Football Bowl Subdivision in tackles for loss each of the last two seasons, had 10 tackles for loss and held the Yellow Jackets to 57 yards rushing. 
Georgia Tech entered the game ranked sixth nationally with an average of 311 yards per game.
